CONVERSATION AFTER
The "asymmetric attention" model reveals how power disparities between countries lead to lopsided diplomatic dynamics. **Large countries** (major powers) command more resources, so their actions overshadow those of smaller nations, causing minor powers to overvalue their importance to major powers. Conversely, major powers often fail to recognize minor powers’ strategic relevance, leading to mutual misunderstandings. This framework explains why small nations may pursue excessive deference to great powers (e.g., balancing diplomacy or neutrality) to mitigate perceived threats, while major powers remain oblivious to the minor powers’ operational needs and security concerns. The result is a system rife with inefficiencies and unresolved tensions.  

