['Thought Process:  \nThis question asks about the theoretical framework of asymmetric attention in international relations, specifically how it explains power dynamics between large and small nations. I’ll reference the "asymmetric attention" model from the text, which argues that power imbalances lead to differential attention between major and minor actors.  \n\nFrom *Li Xing and Geng Jie’s* work:  \nThe "asymmetric attention" theory posits that large countries (major powers) dominate global discourse and hold disproportionate influence over small countries (minor powers). This creates a one-sided dynamic where minor powers often overestimate the impact of major powers on their security, while major powers underestimate the importance of minor powers—leading to misunderstandings and strained relationships.  \n\nKey points:  \n1. **Power Asymmetry**: Large countries have more resources/capabilities, so their actions disproportionately shape perceptions among minor powers.  \n2. **Overattention to Major Powers**: Small countries prioritize engagement with large nations, fearing neglect or being overlooked.  \n3. **Underattention from Major Powers**: Large nations may ignore minor powers’ concerns due to domestic preoccupations or perceived insignificance.  \n4. **Cognitive Disconnect**: These imbalances foster a "misperception" of threats and alliances, perpetuating tension in the international system.  \n\n', '  \nThe "asymmetric attention" model reveals how power disparities between countries lead to lopsided diplomatic dynamics. **Large countries** (major powers) command more resources, so their actions overshadow those of smaller nations, causing minor powers to overvalue their importance to major powers. Conversely, major powers often fail to recognize minor powers’ strategic relevance, leading to mutual misunderstandings. This framework explains why small nations may pursue excessive deference to great powers (e.g., balancing diplomacy or neutrality) to mitigate perceived threats, while major powers remain oblivious to the minor powers’ operational needs and security concerns. The result is a system rife with inefficiencies and unresolved tensions.  \n\n---\n\nSources Used:\n- small_state_diplo_en_ocr2.docx\n- China Strategic Culture Hypothesis - Yasuhiro Matsuda-cl.txt']
