The Chinese Communist Party (CCP) views Western political systems like constitutional democracy and civil society as threats to its leadership. It labels constitutional democracy as a strategy to dismantle China’s socialist system by promoting individualism and privatization, while civil society is framed as a tool to weaken state governance.  

To counter these influences, the CCP enforces strict ideological unity, aligning media narratives with party lines and censoring dissent. Legal measures, such as internet surveillance, aim to suppress online activism and "purify" public discourse. Ultimately, the party seeks to neutralize Western ideological infiltration by prioritizing party authority over individual rights or democratic processes.

